00:09:13,345 --> 00:09:17,920
<i>30% of Toyokawa is served
by on site systems.</i>

163
00:09:18,426 --> 00:09:23,026
<i>And 100% of excreta is
safely managed</i>

164
00:09:23,532 --> 00:09:27,957
<i>as shown in this SFT, prepared
by Professor Hidenori Harada</i>

165
00:09:28,157 --> 00:09:29,932
<i>of Kyoto University.</i>

166
00:09:31,171 --> 00:09:34,708
So why does faecal sludge management
works so well in Japan?

167
00:09:35,938 --> 00:09:38,125
Due to the enabling environment.

168
00:09:38,661 --> 00:09:41,811
<i>There's a system of laws
and enforcement in place</i>

169
00:09:42,011 --> 00:09:46,011
<i>to ensure that every year,
on site systems are inspected</i>

170
00:09:46,211 --> 00:09:49,861
<i>and maintained by a licensed
service provider.</i>

171
00:09:50,951 --> 00:09:55,301
<i>Collection and transport companies
are licensed and regulated.</i>

172
00:09:56,239 --> 00:09:59,226
<i>Legal discharge of faecal 
sludge is subsidised.</i>

173
00:10:00,401 --> 00:10:03,964
<i>The installation and manufacture
of on site systems</i>

174
00:10:04,164 --> 00:10:08,639
<i>is regulated and as our on site
discharge standards.</i>

175
00:10:10,123 --> 00:10:14,035
So what has generated the successes
in all 3 of these cities?

